Lab 08 - User ID Controlled by Request Parameter with Unpredictable User IDs
Objective
Exploit a horizontal privilege escalation vulnerability by discovering Carlos's GUID (Globally Unique Identifier), accessing his account, and retrieving his API key.

Background
Many applications replace predictable identifiers (such as usernames or numeric IDs) with randomly generated values like UUIDs or GUIDs.

Example:

/my-account?id=5d8fae32-b6fc-41f5-9d8d-6ef2b5ef3f65
Developers often assume that because these identifiers cannot be guessed, users cannot access other accounts.

However, unpredictable identifiers are not an access control mechanism. If the application exposes these identifiers elsewhere, an attacker can still obtain them and exploit missing authorization checks.

Vulnerability
Horizontal Privilege Escalation (IDOR)

The application relied solely on a user-controlled GUID to determine which account should be displayed.

Although the identifier was difficult to guess, it was publicly exposed through another part of the application.

The server failed to verify whether the authenticated user was authorized to access the requested account.

