Reconnaissance
The first objective was to discover whether the application exposed user identifiers elsewhere.

Browsed the public blog.

Opened several blog posts.

Observed that posts displayed the author's name.

Clicked on the author Carlos.

The application opened Carlos's public profile page.

The URL contained Carlos's GUID.

This demonstrated that the supposedly "secret" identifier was publicly accessible.

Methodology
Step 1 – Obtain Your Own GUID
Logged into the account page and observed the GUID in the URL.

Example:

/my-account?id=<your-guid>
Step 2 – Search for Carlos
Browsed public blog posts.

Located a post written by Carlos.

Clicked Carlos's username.

Step 3 – Discover Carlos's GUID
Carlos's public profile page exposed his GUID.

This GUID was copied for further testing.

Step 4 – Modify the Request
Changed the account URL from:

/my-account?id=<your-guid>
to

/my-account?id=<carlos-guid>
Step 5 – Observe the Response
The server returned Carlos's account information, including:

Username
Email
API Key
No authorization checks were performed.

Step 6 – Submit Solution
Copied Carlos's API key.

Submitted it to complete the lab.

Why the Attack Worked
The application believed that using unpredictable identifiers was sufficient protection.

Internally, the logic resembled:

user = database.find(request.GET["id"])
show_account(user)
The server never verified whether the authenticated user actually owned the requested account.

A secure implementation would include an authorization check such as:

user = database.find(request.GET["id"])

if user != session.user:
    return 403

show_account(user)
