Key Learning Points
Random identifiers are not security controls.
Hidden identifiers are frequently leaked elsewhere in an application.
Authorization must be enforced regardless of how unpredictable an identifier appears.
IDOR vulnerabilities remain exploitable even when GUIDs are used.
Pentester's Perspective
When testing applications that use UUIDs or GUIDs, never assume they cannot be exploited.

Always search for identifier leakage in:

Public profiles
Blog authors
Comments
API responses
JavaScript files
HTML source
Network traffic
Search functionality
If another user's identifier can be discovered anywhere, immediately test whether it can be used to access protected resources.

This is one of the most common real-world IDOR scenarios.

